MR BOLING WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM HIS 8500 GALLON TRANSPORT INTO A 100 GALLON  CUSTOMER TANK. THROUGH A 2" PRESSURE HOSE. THE HOOKUP CONNECTION IS ABOVE HIS HEAD. HE LAID THE HOSE ON TOP OF THE 1000 GALLON TANK AND CLIMBED  TO THE TOP OF THE 1000 GALLON TANK TO MAKE THE CONNECTION. AS HE REACHED FOR THE HOSE, IT SLID TO THE GROUND, THE BLOCKING VALUE ON THE END OF THE HOSE WAS KNOCKED OPEN AND THE  ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CONTAINED IN THE HOSE WAS DISCHARGED ON TO THE FRONT OF MR BOLINGS PERSON CAUSING CHEMICAL BURNS. MR BOLING WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. A LADDER PLATFORM HAS BEEN INSTALLED AT TANK CONNECTION TO AVOID FUTURE INJURY.
CAR KCC WAS FOUND ON TRACK LEAKING SULFURIC ACID AT DOME. RUPTURE DISC REPL ACED AND CAR WAS FORWARDED ON TO FINAL DESTINATION.

DRIVER WAS BACKED INTO UNLOADING STALL, HAD HOOKED UP HIS HOSE AND WAS PRESSURING OFF.  THE UNLODING HOSE SPRUNG A LEAK NEAR THE END BEHIND THE HOSE FITTINGS.  THEDRIVER RAN THROUGH THE BUILDING AND AROUND HIS TRUCK AND SHUT THE VALVE ON THE UNLOADING LINE.  THE ACID HAD SPRAYED ON THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND ON THE BUILDING, WATER WAS USED TO WASH BOTH OFF. THE ACID THAT WAS ON THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND PLACED IN A HAZARD WASTE DUMPSTER AT THE SITE THERE AT JOHNSON CONTROLS.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: AT 2:20 P.M., WAS CONTACTED BY MS. DIANE TAYLOR, CAR DEPARTMENT, ADVISING THAT CARMAN JIM BALES HAD REPORTED CSXT 483124 WAS SETTING ON TRACK 24 HAVING A GREENISH LIQUID SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM IT. THIS SUBSTANCE HAD FLOWED ALONG THE ROADWAY TOWARD THE CAR DEPARTMENT OFFICE BUILDING. THE PRODUCT HAD FLOWED FROM THE RAIL CAR 330 FEET EASTWARDLY AND WAS LEECHING UNDER TRACK 521. THERE WAS A LARGE STANDING POOL OF WATER APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET LONG, 15 FEET WIDE, AND 4 INCHES DEEP, BETWEEN TRACKS 521 AND 522. AT 4:15 P.M., UTILIZING A SKIM POOL CONTAINMENT DEVICE, PLACED THE SKIM POOL UNDER THE CAR AT THE LOCATION OF THE DRIPPING PRODUCT WHICH WAS UNDER THE CENTER JPORTION OF THE CAR. CAR WAS ALSO DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM EACH OF THE FOUR CORNERS AND A SUITABLE RECEPTICAL WAS PLACED AT EACH LOCATION, WHICH WAS TOTALLY CAPTURING PRODUCT BEING RELEASED.  THIS RELEASE WAS OCCURRING DUE TO THE FACT THE POLYETHALENE COVER WAS DETERIORATING AND, HAVING HAD EXCEPTIONALLY HEAVY RAINS WHICH RESULTED IN THE PRODUCT BEING WASHED FROM THE MATERIALS WITHIN THE CAR.

the spill occured during the unloading process; in whcih the hose, connecting from cargo tank to cutomer piping, blew off due to restraining wire BREAK.  THE HOSE BELONGED TO CONSIGNEE.  DRIVER IMMEDIATLY CLOSED CARGO TANK VALVE AND NOTIFIED CONSIGNEE AND SUPERVISOR.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN GROUND AREA AT UNLOADING SITE AND THEN PICKED UP WITH A VACUUM TRACK.  JAMES HEARD WAS NOTIFIED BY PHONE AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE NUMBER AS WELL AS THE KANSA EPA.  KANSAS EPA ALSO MADE AN INSPECTION AFTER CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETE.  FUTURE INSPECTIONS SHOULD BE MADE OF HOSES, ON A REGULAR BASIS AND BEFORE UNLOADING, TO INSURE INTEGRITY.

column14: CANTON ST BROOK ST CENTRAL ST
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:20 AM OUR VACUUM TRAILER #009 (NEW HAMPSHIRE T43660) ARRIVEDAT OUR FACILITY IN STOUGHTON LEAKING WASTE OIL OUT OF THE SCRUBBER VALVE ON THERIGHT FRONT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. THIS DEVICE IS USED TO RELIEVE PRESSURE ORVACUUM FROM THE TANK AND SHOULD BE CLOSED WHEN NOT IN USE. IT IS APPARENT THATTHE TRUCK DRIVER DID NOT COMPLETELY CLOSE THE VALVE AFTER PICKING UP HIS LASTLOAD AND EVACUATING HIS EQUIPMENT, AS UPON INSPECTION ONE OF OUR MECHANICSDETERMINED THAT THE SCRUBBING SYSTEM WAS MECHANICALLY SOUND. WHEN I WAS CALLEDOUT TO THE TRUCK PARKING AREA OF OUR SITE, I FOLLOWED AN APPROXIMATE ON (1")INCH WIDE LINE OF BLACK OIL DOWN OUR DRIVEWAY TO CANTON STREET AND THEN TO THENORTHWEST ON THIS ROAD AND FINALLY TO THE NORTH LONG BROOK STREET. IT ALSOSEEMED THAT THERE WAS SOME PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE SOUTH ON CENTRAL STREET ASFAR AS THE MBTA RAIL CROSSING. I WOULD ESTIMATE THAT THE TOTAL AMONT RELEASEDWAS SOMEWHERE BETWEEN FIVE (5) AND FIFTEEN (150 GALLONS. STORM DRAINS ANDSURFACE WATERS WERE NOT EFFECTED. I IMMEDIATELY GOT BACK TO OUR YARD ANDMOBILIZED OUR MEN AND MATERIAL TO BROOK AND CENTRAL STREETS TO CLEAN-UP THOSEEFFECTED AREAS. THE CLEANING OF OUR DRIVEWAY HAD ALREADY BEGUN. BEFORE I COULDCALL THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, I WAS CALLED BY THEIR MR. RANDY RICE.I RETURNED HIS CALL IN ORDER TO REPORT SOON AFTERWARDS. THE CLEAN-UP WASCOMPLETED BY 10:20AM AND THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS (APPROXIMATELY SIXTY(60LBS) POUNDS WERE DISPOSED IN OUR FACILITY COMPACTION AREA.
